<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06260007 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06260007 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  OBITUARY; NAME; LIST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  FAIRBANK, John King, 84, a former U.S. official in China and longtime Asiascholar; Saturday of a heart attack. Mr. Fairbank was director of HarvardUniversity's East Asian Research Center from 1955 to 1973. Mr. Fairbank was aformer special assistant to the U.S. ambassador and director of the U.S.Information Service in China. In 1979 he accompanied Vice President WalterMondale on an official visit to China.;   FRIEDMAN, Ike, 67, who developedBorsheim's Fine Jewelry of Omaha into one of the highest-volume jewelry storesin the nation; Thursday of lung cancer in Omaha, Neb. Mr. Friedman joinedBorsheim's in 1950 and became president of the firm in 1973.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  DEATHS ELSEWHERE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO><TEXT>     GREEN, Art, 93, a radio and television personality in the 1950s and 1960sin New York and Miami; Tuesday of a heart attack in Miami. Mr. Green was alawyer in New York in the 1930s before switching to broadcasting. He workedfor several New York radio stations, spinning Big Band records and talkingpolitics.;   HAMILTON, Robert, 58, physician for the DePaul Universityathletic department; Friday of a heart attack in Chicago. Mr. Hamilton hadbeen the team physician since 1964. He also was a clinical professor oforthopedics at the University of Illinois College of Medicine.;   HARRIS,Milton, a prominent chemist whose research ranged from finding ways of keepingwool from shrinking to a substitute for sperm whale oil; Thursday of stomachcancer at his home in Chevy Chase, Md. Mr. Harris was with Gillette Corp. from1956 to 1966, serving as director of research and as a vice president.;  ISRAEL, Adrian C., an investment banker and former president of Bache andamp; Co.;Friday of heart failure at Northern Westchester Hospital Center in MountKisco, N.Y. When he died, Mr. Israel was president and chairman of A.C. IsraelEnterprises, an investment firm in White Plains, N.Y. Much of Mr. Israel'scareer was spent at Bache andamp; Co., which he joined as a limited partner in1945.;   KELLEY, Robert W., 71, a former photographer for Life magazine;Wednesday of cancer in Seattle. After stints with the SeattlePost-Intelligencer and the Seattle Times, Mr. Kelley began working for Life in1947 and was made a staff photographer in 1952. He worked for Life until1966.;   PETERS, Martha, a journalist, advertising writer and public relationsexecutive; Tuesday after suffering respiratory problems in El Paso, Texas.Mrs. Peters wrote a bimonthly book column for the El Paso Times and alsoserved as book editor and coordinated book reviews.;   PIAZZA, Ben, 58, astage, screen and television actor; Sept. 7 of cancer at a Sherman Oakshospital. Mr. Piazza appeared on Broadway in the 1950s in such classics as&quot;Sweet Bird of Youth&quot; and &quot;Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?&quot; He won the1958-'59 Theater World Award for his work in &quot;Kataki.&quot; Mr. Piazza made hismovie debut in &quot;The Hanging Tree&quot; in 1959, and later appeared in &quot;Mask.&quot;;  SEDGWICK Jr., Ellery, 82, a former president and chairman of Medusa Corp. ofCleveland Heights, Ohio, a leading cement maker; Sunday of a heart attack athis home in Gates Mills, Ohio.;   WEINTRAUB, Louis, 69, a New York publicrelations and picture-service executive for more than 40 years; Friday of aheart attack at his home in Jericho, N.Y. Mr. Weintraub was chairman ofWeintraub andamp; FitzSimons Inc., and of Photo Communications Inc. In World War II,he was a Signal Corps combat photographer and served throughout the Europeancampaign.;   WELCH, Brother Bernard Alfred, 82, who retired in 1974 after 38years on the faculty of Manhattan College; Tuesday of cancer at De La SalleHall, a Christian Brothers residence in Lincroft, N.J.;   WILSON, JohnFletcher, 68, professor emeritus of speech and theater at Lehman College inthe Bronx; Tuesday from complications after recent implantation of a cardiacpacemaker at Bellevue Hospital in New York. Mr. Wilson retired two years ago.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910916  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  649  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, September 16, 199100260007,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>